[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'If you have a high-resolution 3D Gaussian [music] splat of a real location, can you use virtual production to stay in a studio but shoot in all of these locations? [music] What are the tools needed to pull this off on an indie budget? And do the production savings outweigh the extra visual'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'effects time you\'ll need? That\'s what I want to find out in this video, and I\'m sharing all the steps along the way. Feel free to skip [music] to the final results and final takeaways. Here\'s what we\'re going to test. With a'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '3D Gaussian splat workflow, can we shoot in four locations around the world in a single day while staying right here at Lightcraft Studios in Los Angeles? I have incredibly high-resolution 3D Gaussian splats from Megascapes [music]'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of a Nevada desert, a London street, and a Toronto alley. I also have an entire virtual production workflow Lightcraft technology has developed with their virtual production app Jetset and new web interface Spark.'

[00:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'First, the project starts with a plan. I\'m using Lightcraft Spark as a pre-production tool so I can plan what we\'re going to test here. It\'s basically like Google Docs of 3D where the entire team can work collaboratively in a 3D'

[01:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'environment without needing to know Maya or Blender or Unreal Engine. You upload a script, add a new scene, and then add any elements that you need. Then you can create specific shots to specific parts of your script. This pre-vis is'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'incredibly helpful because it allows the crew and cast to see exactly what we\'re going to be doing. Exporting from Spark generates a QR code that opens the scene right in the Jetset app.'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; The iPhone is attached to the camera, locked in place, and a video feed from the camera goes to the iPhone through an Accsoon CineEye which converts our SDI or HDMI out and puts that into the iPhone. We capture reference frames, and the offset of the'

[01:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'iPhone lens and the lens on the cinema camera are calculated. So, all our tracking data matches the footage we\'re shooting with the cinema camera. You can do this for as many lenses as you plan on using for the day. Today, I\'m being helped by cinematographer Guillermo'

[01:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Cameo and gaffer Andrew Torbetson. It\'s their first time using Jetset, but I was able to show them the steps along the way. &gt;&gt; We\'re going to point [music] to something that is as complex as possible. Get a bunch of reference frames in an arc.'

[02:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; Mhm. To get some parallaxing. Because it\'s red, it hasn\'t been calibrated yet, but it\'s basically saying this within here is what your camera is seeing. Ah. We\'re going to run it through the computer and then you\'ll be able to'

[02:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'toggle it where instead of seeing this version, we can pull the feed directly in there. So you\'re going to see [music] directly from your camera. Nice. Um so to do that, we\'re going to go to the computer. &gt;&gt; To run the lens calibration, we\'re going to use Lightcraft\'s desktop application'

[02:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'called AutoShot. If you\'ve watched any of my videos on virtual production or making tidbits and bites specifically, you\'ll recognize this AutoShot interface. Eventually, it\'ll be folded into Spark, so it\'ll have a beautiful'

[02:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'facelift, but for now, we\'re using this one. The last thing we need Do you know the sensor width? Uh it\'s a Super 35 in theory. Let me double check. 24.88 by 14. So now it\'s crunching all of that data.'

[02:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And then it\'s going to push it back to the phone. Magic. There we go. Crazy. Cool. Yeah. Beautiful.'

[03:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We\'re going to shoot the desert scene in the sunlight in a park across the street. We\'re using a pop-up green screen and orbiting around the actor so that we can get some really interesting parallaxing to really show off that'

[03:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'these are 3D environments and not just, [music] you know, 2D image plates behind our actor. Then we\'re going to shoot the Toronto alley on a green [music] screen.'

[03:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We\'re still lighting the green screen, so while we wait, we\'re going to grab a quick shot out here that takes place on a London street. To match the lighting in the 3D Gaussian splat, we are shooting in the shade so that the natural light on our actress matches'

[03:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what the background environment\'s going to be, and shooting outdoors in natural light [music] really adds to the realism here. As you\'ll see in the final shot later. Now, we\'re going to shoot our night'

[04:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'exterior in the Toronto alley. So, our company move is from the parking lot to the studio instead of from London to Toronto. Jetset [music] uses the iPhone\'s AR kit to do its camera tracking. In Jetset, we can get a 3D scan of the environment,'

[04:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which will give me a mesh of our set that I can use later in the VFX process. It allows me to know the real location of all our lights so I can match them in the digital environment. Then you shoot your scene normally. You'

[04:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can see the 3D Gaussian splat in [music] real time in Jetset, and Jetset\'s recording all of that tracking data. The benefits of green screen is that it makes isolating a subject a lot easier. Some tradeoffs are that you have a lot of green spill you need to take care of,'

[04:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and often green screen lighting looks more studio than natural, especially [music] outdoor scenes. But from a production perspective, it\'s great because you\'re in a contained, controlled environment. Our DP and gaffer can run Jetset [music]'

[04:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'on an iPad and explore the scene in real time as if they were on location. They\'re going to set up lights that match this 3D environment. We\'re testing two techniques. One is to have our actor here on a green screen. The other technique is to actually shoot outside'

[05:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'at night uh following behind our actor with a pop-up green screen. [music] And the reason we\'re doing that is because since we\'re filming outside at night with lights, it\'s going to look and feel more like our actor is outside [music] at night and match that background more'

[05:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'than the green screen shot probably will. And that\'s a wrap on production. Now, it\'s time to take our footage, all of that tracking data, and the 3D Gaussian splats made by Megascapes, and put together our final shots.'

[05:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'While we saved a ton of time and money on production with the Gaussian splat workflow, it comes with the tradeoff of an entire post-production [music] workflow. So, here are the steps of that workflow. To get all of the camera'

[05:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tracking data out of Jetset, we\'re going to use Auto Shot by Lightcraft. Here I can select the take, point to the footage from my camera, and the frames of the shot I\'m going to use. Because I\'m using 3D Gaussian splats, I\'m going [music] to use Unreal Engine. This will'

[05:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generate a Python script that you can put in the command console. In Unreal Engine, you\'ll need to activate these plugins for the Auto Shot script to work. For Gaussian splats, Unreal Engine also needs a plugin. I\'m'

[06:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'using Volinga, and I have another video breakdown for how this plugin works, including relighting Gaussian splats. The Auto Shot script will create a camera, have your footage on an image plane, and import the mesh of the 3D'

[06:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scan of your scene. Then I render out the background. Next, I\'m compositing my shots in Nuke. First, I render out my footage as an EXR sequence in an ACES color space. Then it\'s a matter of'

[06:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'keying and rotoscoping. This is part of the process that\'s unavoidable. While there are some AI rotoscoping options out there, it works best for wide shots or just for garbage mats. For this hair detail, you\'re going to need to go in'

[06:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and do it the old-fashioned way. And this is the trade-off of this workflow. This is by far the step that took the longest to complete, [music] and of course, it\'s just mentioned here as you watch it all happen super fast on screen. When I got through these first'

[06:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shots, we decided we wanted to see some wider shots as well. So, I went back to the Lightcraft studio parking lot and did a pickup shoot with my Blackmagic camera and a wider lens. I wanted to composite some shots where we\'re actually seeing the ground itself, get'

[07:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'those real shadows and contact shadows, which will really help sell the realism. I also tried a couple of different techniques. We did a full wet down of the pavement so we could get some reflections from lights, and also set these aperture infinite bars to a siren'

[07:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mode to get some interactive lighting because that change in lighting between the foreground and background is really going to sell the composite. This is the other reason why I\'m using Volinga in Unreal Engine because with Volinga, you can relight Gaussian splats. The'

[07:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'workflow for these shots was the same, but because we see the ground, the tracking needs to be perfect. Here\'s where something came up I didn\'t think about. Because the splat is a point cloud, there\'s no solid mesh. So, even'

[07:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with Auto Shot Tracking Refinement Tools using Syntheyes, there\'s a question of where [music] is the floor plane? Is it sitting on top of the splat, halfway submerged by the splat, or is it even lower? Getting this sub-pixel accurate'

[08:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'level of detail is crucial, especially when you are putting a shot together that\'s intended to be watched on a cinema screen. It took me trial and error and some manual adjustments and rendering out the backgrounds a few'

[08:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'times to get something that eventually worked. Some challenging factors I was running into were that one, that I don\'t have obviously that mesh ground [music] plane in the Gaussian splat, and two, the ground in the parking lot was sloped'

[08:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for this drainage area. So, that meant doing a lot of manual rotation of my scene to make sure that this ground was flat and then lined up with the splat itself. [music]'

[08:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But, it was all worth it because seeing the ground in these shots really ties the actors into the background [music] very nicely. The lighting isn\'t a perfect match because [music] we just threw up some aperture and finna bars on this pickup'

[08:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shoot, but it\'s enough to sell it. The interactive lighting with the flashes and the wet down on the ground turned [music] out great. One thing I\'m actually surprised by is that the indoor and outdoor green screen shots both look identical. [music] It goes to show that'

[09:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Guillermo and Andrew did a great job making sure that the lighting they were setting up matched [music] very specific parts of the splat. The big difference is the amount of room we had. The tracking shot feels more dynamic because we had the entire parking lot to walk'

[09:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'through versus just panning back and forth inside. I could just go in and work on some of these hair edges a little bit more. I have the detail here from the key. It\'s just getting [music] rid of the green using the IBK gizmo caused some chattering-ness. But, little'

[09:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'things like that really just boil down to how many revisions am I actually going to do on these shots For testing out this workflow, this is just a compositing thing. As far as the things that I wasn\'t sure about and what we were testing [music] with Gaussian'

[09:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'splats and virtual production, everything with Mega Scapes and Light Craft works perfectly. So, here are the finished shots. Then I\'ll give you a final breakdown. &gt;&gt; [music]'

[09:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; Where was this workflow time-saver and'

[12:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'where did it add unnecessary complexity? [music] For production, it was definitely more efficient. Instead of sending a casting crew around the world, you could send one person with a scanner and then keep your crew in one location. That\'s excellent. If you watched the'

[12:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'behind-the-scenes of my friends of Sophia series, you know that building 3D environments [music] takes a lot of time. Getting all of those little details right. With the Gaussian splats of real locations, I got to skip that step entirely, which was'

[12:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'wonderful. But then, there\'s a lot of post-work. And as you saw, it takes finesse. [music] With big sci-fi vistas, if things aren\'t perfect, it\'s all right. It\'s sci-fi and it\'s stylized. For something where you\'re intending to use this workflow'

[12:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '[music] to look as if you shot on location, it takes a little bit more work in post. The question is, is 3 weeks of visual effects cheaper than your production costs? That depends on what kind of shoot you have going on. Let me know if'

[13:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you have any leftover questions about this whole workflow.'
